If the roots are \(r, s, t\), then the polynomial can be written as \((x - r)(x - s)(x - t)\). Expanding this, we get: \[ x^3 - (r + s + t)x^2 + (rs + rt + st)x - rst \] Comparing coefficients, we find: - \(a = -(r + s + t)\) - \(b = rs + rt + st\) - The constant term is \(-rst = 6\), so \(rst = -6\). We need to find all ordered triples \((r, s, t)\) of distinct integers such that their product is \(-6\). The possible multisets of roots are: 1. All positive: \(\{1, 2, 3\}\) 2. All negative: \(\{-1, -2, -3\}\) 3. One negative and two positive: \(\{-1, 1, 6\}\), \(\{-2, 1, 3\}\), \(\{-3, 1, 2\}\) For each multiset, we calculate \(a\) and \(b\): 1. \(\{1, 2, 3\}\): - Sum: \(1 + 2 + 3 = 6\) �� \(a = -6\) - Product pairs: \(1 \cdot 2 + 1 \cdot 3 + 2 \cdot 3 = 11\) �� \(b = 11\) - Pair: \((-6, 11)\) 2. \(\{-1, -2, -3\}\): - Sum: \(-1 + (-2) + (-3) = -6\) �� \(a = 6\) - Product pairs: \((-1)(-2) + (-1)(-3) + (-2)(-3) = 11\) �� \(b = 11\) - Pair: \((6, 11)\) 3. \(\{-1, 1, 6\}\): - Sum: \(-1 + 1 + 6 = 6\) �� \(a = -6\) - Product pairs: \((-1)(1) + (-1)(6) + 1 \cdot 6 = -1\) �� \(b = -1\) - Pair: \((-6, -1)\) 4. \(\{-2, 1, 3\}\): - Sum: \(-2 + 1 + 3 = 2\) �� \(a = -2\) - Product pairs: \((-2)(1) + (-2)(3) + 1 \cdot 3 = -5\) �� \(b = -5\) - Pair: \((-2, -5)\) 5. \(\{-3, 1, 2\}\): - Sum: \(-3 + 1 + 2 = 0\) �� \(a = 0\) - Product pairs: \((-3)(1) + (-3)(2) + 1 \cdot 2 = -7\) �� \(b = -7\) - Pair: \((0, -7)\) The distinct ordered pairs \((a, b)\) are \((-6, 11)\), \((6, 11)\), \((-6, -1)\), \((-2, -5)\), and \((0, -7)\).
